source_code.code:
public static void main(String[] args) {
	Display display = new Display();
	Shell shell = new Shell(display);
	final Table table = new Table(shell, SWT.NONE);
	table.setLinesVisible(true);
	table.setHeaderVisible(true);
	String[] titles = {"C1", "C2", "C3"};
	for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
		new TableColumn(table, SWT.NULL).setText(titles[i]);
	}
	for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
		new TableItem(table, SWT.NULL).setText(new String[] 
{"a","b","c"});
	}
	for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
		table.getColumn(i).pack();
	}
	table.setSize(table.computeSize(SWT.DEFAULT, 100));
	shell.pack();
	shell.open();
	table.addListener(SWT.MouseDown, new Listener() {
		public void handleEvent(Event event) {
			TableColumn[] columns = table.getColumns();
			for (int i = columns.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
				columns[i].dispose();  // !!!!!
			}
		}
	});
	while (!shell.isDisposed()) {
		if (!display.readAndDispatch())
			display.sleep();
	}
	display.dispose();
}

Bug.WithStack:
Hi!

I'm coding a TableModel for SWT Table. 
I got serious troubles, when I tried to dispose TableColumns. Everything is 
alright till the moment when you want to dispose the last(!) TableColumn of the 
Table -> IndexOutOfBound Exception. (I think the reason is, that a Table is 
internally initialised with 1 TableColumn?)

So I just see two possibilities ... and both are not really practicable.

1) Dispose the whole Table and instance it once more.
2) Do not dispose the last TableColumn, just remove the TableItems and set the 
text of the TableColumn  to "". -> This possibilitie causes logical 
implementations in the source to handle the situation that although all columns 
should be disposed ... there is still one...

I tried possibility 2) and wanted to add Columns, Rows and Values again I 
notices a weird behaviour of the Table(Columns).

